{"title_page": "Cellophane noodles", "text_new": "{{short description|Transparent noodle made from starch}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Cellophane noodles\n| image            = Cooked dangmyeon.jpg\n| caption          = Cooked cellophane noodles\n| alternate_name   = Glass noodles\n| country          = [[China]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Hulin |first=Belinda |date=November 10, 2009 |title=Knack Chinese Cooking |publisher=Globe Pequot Press |page=150 |isbn=9780762758463}}</ref>\n| region           = [[East Asia]], [[Southeast Asia]], [[Indian subcontinent]] \n| national_cuisine = [[Chinese cuisine|China]], [[Indian cuisine|India]], [[Indonesian cuisine|Indonesia]], [[Japanese cuisine|Japan]], [[Korean cuisine|Korea]], [[Malaysian cuisine|Malaysia]], [[Filipino cuisine|Philippines]], [[Samoan cuisine|Samoa]], [[Thai cuisine|Thailand]], [[American cuisine|United States]], [[Vietnamese cuisine|Vietnam]], and [[Taiwanese cuisine|Taiwan]]\n| creator          = \n| year             = \n| mintime          = \n| maxtime          = \n| type             = [[Noodle]]s\n| course           = \n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Starch]] (from [[mung bean]]s, [[Yam (vegetable)|yams]], [[potato starch|potatoes]], [[cassava]], [[Canna (plant)|canna]], or [[Sweet potato|batata]]), water\n| minor_ingredient = \n| variations       = \n| serving_size     = \n| calories         = \n| calories_ref     = \n| protein          = \n| fat              = \n| carbohydrate     = \n| glycemic_index   = \n| similar_dish     = \n| other            = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| title            = Regional name\n| hide             = no\n| name1            = Chinese name\n| t                = \u7c89\u7d72\n| s                = \u7c89\u4e1d\n| l                = flour thread\n| p                = f\u011bns\u012b\n| w                = f\u00ean<sup>3</sup>-ss\u016d<sup>1</sup>\n| y                = f\u00e1n s\u012b\n| j                = fan<sup>2</sup> si<sup>1</sup>\n| altname          = Chinese name (Taiwan)\n| c2               = \u51ac\u7c89\n| l2               = winter flour\n| p2               = d\u014dngf\u011bn\n| w2               = tung<sup>1</sup>-f\u00ean<sup>3</sup>\n| bpmf2            = \u3109\u3128\u3125\u3108\u3123\u02c7\n| poj2             = tang-h\u00fan\n| hangul           = \ub2f9\uba74\n| hanja            = \u5510\u9eb5\n| rr               = dangmyeon\n| mr               = tangmy\u014fn\n| lk               = [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] noodle\n| nkhangul         = \ubd84\ud0d5\n| nkhanja          = \u7c89\u6e6f\n| nkmr             = punt'ang\n| nkrr             = buntang\n| nklk             = flour soup\n| kanji            = \u6625\u96e8\n| kana             = \u306f\u308b\u3055\u3081\n| revhep           = harusame\n| tgl              = sotanghon\n| ind              = sohun\n| tha              = \u0e27\u0e38\u0e49\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19 / \u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19\u0e41\u0e01\u0e07\u0e23\u0e49\u0e2d\u0e19 / \u0e15\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e19\n| rtgs             = wun sen / sen kaeng ron / tung hon\n| vie              = mi\u1ebfn / b\u00fan t\u00e0u\n| lqn              = noodle / Chinese vermicelli\n}}\n'''Cellophane noodles''', or '''fensi''' ({{zh|s=\u7c89\u4e1d|p=f\u011bns\u012b|l=flour thread|t=\u7c89\u7d72}}), sometimes called '''glass noodles''', are a type of transparent [[noodle]] made from [[starch]] (such as [[mung bean]] starch, [[potato starch]], [[sweet potato]] starch, [[tapioca]], or [[canna (plant)|canna]] starch) and water.\n\nThey are generally sold in dried form, soaked to reconstitute, then used in soups, stir-fried dishes, or [[spring roll]]s. They are called \"cellophane noodles\" or \"glass noodles\" because of their [[cellophane]]- or [[glass]]-like transparency when cooked.\nCellophane noodles should not be confused with [[rice vermicelli]], which are made from [[rice]] and are white in color rather than clear (after cooking in water).\n\n== Varieties ==\nCellophane noodles are made from a variety of [[starch|starches]]. In China, cellophane noodles are usually made of [[mung bean]] starch. Chinese varieties made from [[mung bean]] starch are called '''Chinese vermicelli''', '''bean threads''', or '''bean thread noodles'''. Thicker Korean varieties made with sweet potato starch are called '''sweet potato noodles''' or '''''dangmyeon'''''.\n\nCellophane noodles are available in various thicknesses. Wide, flat cellophane noodle sheets called '''[[mung bean sheet]]s''' are also produced in China. In Korea, '''''napjak-dangmyeon''''' (literally \"flat ''dangmyeon\"'') refers to flat sweet potato noodles.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Dongfen.JPG|Dried Chinese vermicelli made with [[mung bean]] starch\nFile:Dangmyeon.jpg|Dried Korean ''dangmyeon'' made with [[sweet potato]] starch\nFile:Dong bei da la pi.jpg|''D\u014dng b\u011bi d\u00e0 l\u0101 p\u00ed'' made with Chinese [[mung bean sheet]]s\nFile:Napjak-dangmyeon in jjimdak.jpg|''Napjak-dangmyeon'' in ''[[jjimdak]]''\n</gallery>\n\n== Production ==\nIn China, the primary site of production of cellophane noodles is the town of Zhangxing, in [[Zhaoyuan, Shandong|Zhaoyuan]], [[Shandong]] province. However, historically the noodles were shipped through the port of [[Longkou]], and thus the noodles are known and marketed as Longkou ''fensi'' ({{zh|s=[[wikt:\u9f99\u53e3|\u9f99\u53e3]][[wikt:\u7c89\u4e1d|\u7c89\u4e1d]]|t=[[wikt:\u9f8d\u53e3|\u9f8d\u53e3]][[wikt:\u7c89\u7d72|\u7c89\u7d72]]}}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.made-in-china.com/import-export/umnEfQJVBxdZprofile1/Yantaiyinsida-Longkou-Vermicelli-Co-Ltd-.html|title=China Vermicelli Manufacturer - Yantai Yinsida Longkou Vermicelli Co., Ltd.|publisher=made-in-china.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927105309/http://www.made-in-china.com/import-export/umnEfQJVBxdZprofile1/Yantaiyinsida-Longkou-Vermicelli-Co-Ltd-.html|archivedate=2007-09-27}}</ref>\n\n== Use ==\n\n=== China ===\n[[File:Mayishangshu.jpg|thumb|''[[Ants climbing a tree]]'' (\u879e\u87fb\u4e0a\u6a39)]]\nIn [[Chinese language|Chinese]], the most commonly used names are ''f\u011bns\u012b'' ({{zh|first=c|c=[[wikt:\u7c89\u7d72|\u7c89\u7d72]]}}, literally \"noodle thread\") and ''d\u014dngf\u011bn'' ({{zh|t=[[wikt:\u51ac|\u51ac]][[wikt:\u7c89|\u7c89]]}}, literally \"winter noodle\"). They are also marketed under the name ''saifun'', the [[Cantonese language|Cantonese]] pronunciation of the Mandarin ''x\u00ecf\u011bn'' ({{zh|c=[[wikt:\u7d30|\u7d30]][[wikt:\u7c89|\u7c89]]}}; literally \"slender noodle\"), though the name ''f\u00e1ns\u012b'' (\u7c89\u7d72) is the term most often used in Cantonese.\n\nIn China, cellophane noodles are a popular ingredient used in [[stir frying|stir fries]], soups, and particularly [[hot pot]]s. They can also be used as an ingredient in fillings for a variety of Chinese ''[[jiaozi]]'' (dumplings) and ''[[Bing (Chinese flat bread)|bing]]'' ([[flatbreads]]), especially in [[vegetarian]] versions of these dishes. Thicker cellophane noodles are also commonly used to imitate the appearance and texture of [[Shark fin soup|shark's fin]] in vegetarian soups. Thicker varieties, most popular in China's [[Northeast China|northeast]], are used in stir fries as well as cold salad-like dishes. A popular soup using the ingredient is fried tofu with thin noodles ({{zh|first=c|c=[[wikt:\u6cb9|\u6cb9]][[wikt:\u8c46|\u8c46]][[wikt:\u8150|\u8150]][[wikt:\u7dda|\u7dda]][[wikt:\u7c89|\u7c89]][[wikt:\u6e6f|\u6e6f]]}}; [[Pinyin]]: ''y\u00f3u d\u00f2u fu-xi\u00e0n f\u011bn t\u0101ng''). A popular [[Szechuan cuisine|Sichuan]] dish called ''[[ants climbing a tree]]'' consists of stewed cellophane noodles with a spicy ground pork meat sauce.\n\n==== Tibet ====\nIn [[Tibetan cuisine]], glass noodles are called ''phing'' or ''fing'' and are used in soup, pork curry or with mushrooms.\n\n=== India ===\nIn [[India]] and [[Pakistan]], glass noodles are called ''falooda'' (see [[falooda]], the dessert dish), and are served on top of ''[[kulfi]]'' (a traditional ice cream). They are usually made from arrowroot starch using a traditional technique. The noodles are flavorless so they provide a nice contrast with the sweet ''kulfi''. ''Kulfi'' and ''falooda'' can be bought from numerous food stalls throughout Pakistan and northern parts of India.\n\n=== Indonesia ===\nIn [[Indonesian cuisine]], they are called ''soun'' or ''suun''.\n\n=== Japan ===\nIn [[Japanese cuisine]], they are called ''harusame'' ({{lang|ja-Hani|[[wikt:\u6625\u96e8|\u6625\u96e8]]}}), literally \"spring rain\". Unlike Chinese glass noodles, they are usually made from potato starch. They are commonly used to make salads, or as an ingredient in [[hot pot]] dishes. They are also often used to make Japanese adaptations of Chinese and Korean dishes. [[Shirataki noodles|''Shirataki'' noodles]] are translucent, traditional Japanese noodles made from the [[konjac]] yam and sometimes [[tofu]].\n\n=== Korea ===\n[[File:Polish Korean Cuisine and Culture Exchanges Gradmother\u2019s Recipes 05.jpg|thumb|''[[Japchae]]'' from Korea]]\nIn [[Korean cuisine]], glass noodles are usually made from [[sweet potato]] starch and are called ''dangmyeon'' ([[Hangul]]: {{lang|ko-Hang|[[wikt:\ub2f9\uba74|\ub2f9\uba74]]}}; [[Hanja]]: {{lang|ko-Hant|[[wikt:\u5510|\u5510]][[wikt:\u9eb5|\u9eb5]]}}; literally \"[[Tang Dynasty|Tang]] noodles\"; also spelled ''dang myun'', ''dangmyun'', ''tang myun'', or ''tangmyun'').  They are commonly stir-fried in sesame oil with beef and vegetables, and flavoured with soy and sugar, in a popular dish called ''[[japchae]]'' (hangul: \uc7a1\ucc44). They are usually thick, and are a brownish-gray color when in their uncooked form.\n\n=== Malaysia ===\nIn [[Malaysia]] and [[Taiwan]] they are known as ''tanghoon'' ([[wikt:\u51ac|\u51ac]][[wikt:\u7c89|\u7c89]]). They are sometimes confused with ''bihun'' ([[wikt:\u7c73\u7c89|\u7c73\u7c89]]) which are [[rice vermicelli]]. Sometimes also known as suhun or suhoon.\n\n=== Philippines ===\n[[File:Sotanghonjf1681.JPG|thumb|Pancit Sotanghon (Lin-Mers, [[Baliuag, Bulacan]]).]]\nIn [[Filipino cuisine]], the noodles are called a similar name: ''sotanghon'' because of the popular dish of the same name made from them using chicken and [[Cloud ear fungus|wood ears]]. They are also confused with rice vermicelli, which is called ''bihon'' in the Philippines.\n\n=== Samoa ===\nGlass noodles were introduced to [[Samoa]] by [[Cantonese]] agricultural workers in the early 1900s where they became known as \"''lialia''\", a Samoan word meaning \"to twirl\", after the method of twirling the noodles around chopsticks when eating. A popular dish called ''sapasui'' (transliteration of the [[Cantonese]] [[chop suey]]) is common fare at social gatherings. Sapasui, a soupy dish of boiled glass noodles mixed with braised pork, beef, or chicken and chopped vegetables, is akin to Hawaiian \"long rice\".\n\n=== Thailand ===\n[[File:Yam wun sen.JPG|thumb|''Yam wun sen kung'': A [[Thai salad]] made with cellophane noodles and prawns]]\nIn [[Thai cuisine]], glass noodles are called ''wun sen'' ({{lang-th|[[wikt:\u0e27\u0e38\u0e49\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19|\u0e27\u0e38\u0e49\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19]]}}). They are commonly mixed with pork and shrimp in a spicy salad called ''yam wun sen'' ({{lang-th|\u0e22\u0e33\u0e27\u0e38\u0e49\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19}}), or stir-fried as ''phat wun sen'' ({{lang-th|\u0e1c\u0e31\u0e14\u0e27\u0e38\u0e49\u0e19\u0e40\u0e2a\u0e49\u0e19}}).\n\n=== United States ===\nIn [[Hawaii]], where cuisine is heavily influenced by Asian cultures, cellophane noodles are known locally as '''long rice''', supposedly because the process of making the noodles involves extruding the starch through a [[potato ricer]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://starbulletin.com/2007/04/25/features/story01.html|date=Apr 25, 2007|title=The choice is clear|author=Keiko Ohnuma|work=Honolulu Star-Bulletin|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614015714/http://starbulletin.com/2007/04/25/features/story01.html|archivedate=June 14, 2008}}</ref>  They are used most often in ''chicken long rice'', a dish of cellophane noodles in chicken broth that is often served at [[luau]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://onokinegrindz.typepad.com/ono_kine_grindz/2005/10/chicken_long_ri.html|title=Chicken Long Rice|date=October 27, 2005|work='Ono Kine Grindz|publisher=[[TypePad]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927125452/http://onokinegrindz.typepad.com/ono_kine_grindz/2005/10/chicken_long_ri.html|archivedate=September 27, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Vietnam ===\nIn [[Vietnamese cuisine]], there are two varieties of cellophane noodles. The first, called ''b\u00fan t\u00e0u'' or ''b\u00fan t\u00e0o'', are made from [[mung bean]] starch, and were introduced by Chinese immigrants. The second, called ''mi\u1ebfn'' or ''mi\u1ebfn dong'', are made from [[Canna (plant)|canna]] ({{lang-vi|dong ri\u1ec1ng}}), and were developed in Vietnam. These cellophane noodles are a main ingredient in the dishes: ''mi\u1ebfn g\u00e0'', ''mi\u1ebfn l\u01b0\u01a1n'', ''mi\u1ebfn m\u0103ng v\u1ecbt'', and ''mi\u1ebfn cua''. These cellophane noodles are sometimes confused with rice vermicelli ([[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]: [[b\u00fan]]) and [[arrowroot]] starch noodles ([[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]: arrowroot: ''c\u1ee7 dong'', arrowroot starch: ''b\u1ed9t dong/b\u1ed9t ho\u00e0ng tinh/b\u1ed9t m\u00ec tinh'').\n\n==Health concerns==\nIn 2004, a number of companies producing [[Longkou]] cellophane noodles produced in [[Yantai]], [[Shandong]] were discovered to be [[Food safety incidents in China|adulterated]], with unscrupulous companies making noodles from [[cornstarch]] instead of green beans in order to reduce costs; the companies, to make the cornstarch transparent, were adding [[sodium formaldehyde sulfoxylate]] and lead-based whiteners to their noodles.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|author=Yunxiang Yan|title=From Food Poisoning to Poisonous Food: The Spectrum of Food-Safety Problems in Contemporary China|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wx-jBgAAQBAJ|work=Re-orienting Cuisine: East Asian Foodways in the Twenty-First Century|editor=Kwang Ok Kim|publisher=Berghahn Books|date=2015|page=272}}</ref> \n\nIn December 2010, Czech food inspection authorities (SZPI) again inspected Chinese cellophane noodles, this time determining that {{convert|142|mg/kg|abbr=on}} of [[aluminium]] had been used in the production of the noodles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.szpi.gov.cz/docDetail.aspx?docid=1027641&docType=ART&nid=11343 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-12-16 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718172850/http://www.szpi.gov.cz/docDetail.aspx?docid=1027641&docType=ART&nid=11343 |archivedate=2011-07-18 }}</ref> Above {{convert|10|mg/kg|abbr=on}} is an illegal amount for noodles in Czech and EU markets (see Annex I to Regulation (EC) No 669/2009 and its amendments (EU) No 187/2011, 618/2013 annex I).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of noodles]]\n* [[Hiyamugi]]\n* [[Kelp noodles]]\n* [[Khanom chin]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.foodsubs.com/NoodlesAsianOther.html Cook's Thesaurus: Other Asian Noodles]\n\n{{Chinese noodles}}\n\n{{Portal|Food}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese noodles]]\n[[Category:Korean noodles]]\n[[Category:Noodles]]\n[[Category:Philippine cuisine]]\n[[Category:Vietnamese noodles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Transparent noodle made from starch}}\n{{Infobox food\n| name             = Cellophane noodles\n| image            = Cooked dangmyeon.jpg\n| caption          = Cooked cellophane noodles\n| alternate_name   = Glass noodles\n| country          = [[China]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Hulin |first=Belinda |date=November 10, 2009 |title=Knack Chinese Cooking |publisher=Globe Pequot Press |page=150 |isbn=9780762758463}}</ref>\n| region           = [[East Asia]], [[Southeast Asia]], [[Indian subcontinent]] \n| national_cuisine = [[Chinese cuisine|China]], [[Indian cuisine|